e,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"82114","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/82114"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA two-year-old boy is admitted to the paediatric ward with a three-day history of barking cough, stridor, and increased work of breathing. He has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. His immunisations are up to date. On examination, he appears mildly distressed with a pulse rate of 130/min, respiratory rate 35/min, SpO2 94% on room air, and temperature 38.2\u00b0C. He has inspiratory stridor at rest and moderate suprasternal recession. A chest X-ray is performed (Image).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following radiological signs is demonstrated on this chest X-ray?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Pencil-point sign","Cotton wool sign","Thumb print sign","Steeple sign","Wine bottle sign"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with classic symptoms of viral croup (laryngotracheobronchitis), including barking cough and stridor. While croup is primarily a clinical diagnosis, chest X-rays may be performed in cases where the diagnosis is unclear or to rule out other conditions.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESteeple sign\u003C/strong\u003E refers to the symmetric narrowing of the subglottic airway that creates an appearance similar to a church steeple or inverted V on an anteroposterior chest X-ray. This narrowing occurs due to subglottic inflammation and oedema, which are hallmarks of croup.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Ewine bottle sign\u003C/strong\u003E (also known as \u0027bottle neck sign\u0027) is seen in achalasia where there is smooth tapering of the lower oesophagus, resembling a wine bottle.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Ethumb print sign\u003C/strong\u003E is seen in epiglottitis where the enlarged epiglottis appears as a thumb-like opacity on lateral neck X-ray. This is a separate condition from croup and represents a medical emergency.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Epencil-point sign\u003C/strong\u003E refers to severe narrowing of the tracheal air column seen in tracheal stenosis, which is typically a chronic condition rather than an acute presentation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Ecotton wool sign\u003C/strong\u003E refers to the appearance of soft, fluffy opacities seen in pulmonary oedema on chest X-ray, which is not relevant to this case of upper airway obstruction.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The steeple sign on chest X-ray represents subglottic narrowing characteristic of croup.","Croup is a clinical diagnosis, with X-rays reserved for cases where the diagnosis is unclear.","The steeple sign appears as symmetric narrowing of the subglottic airway creating an inverted V or church steeple appearance."],"references":["Cisneros V, Zakaria J, Wirachin Hoonpongsimanont. Croup. Journal of Education and Teaching in Emergency Medicine. 2018 Jan 1;3(4). https://jetem.org/croup/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"67310"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"19180"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"21490"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"21490","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/21490"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/k9I7RJBvzfKcENjatd8ZSHv06ZhefQ.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/k9I7RJBvzfKcENjatd8ZSHv06ZhefQ.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":630,"height":630}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"67310","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/67310"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-28T09:15:12+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-28T09:15:59+10:30","number":4,"notes":"","plagiarismCheckedAt":"2025-01-28T09:15:18+10:30","plagiar